THE South African National Defence Force (SANDF) members have been applauded for their sterling job in recovering stolen cars next to the borderline of Mozambique on Saturday, 28 January. According to the Mpumalanga police, SANDF recovered three vehicles – a Toyota Fortuner and two other Toyota bakkies – on Saturday morning at Steenbook Trust outside Komatipoort, near Mozambique. The police said the vehicles were possibly left abandoned by suspects. Police spokesman Brigadier Selvy Mohlala said according to the information they have, the three vehicles were recovered by the SANDF members after being spotted next to the borderline. ALSO READ: Churches seek divine intervention in crime fight Mohlala said police were informed and upon arrival at the scene, they started with investigations. “Preliminary investigations have since revealed that the single-cab bakkie, Toyota Legend 50, was reportedly stolen this month in Alberton, Gauteng. The Toyota Fortuner was also reportedly stolen this month at Mothotlung in the North West province during a hijacking incident. “When zooming into the other recovered Toyota club-cab bakkie, Legend 50, police discovered that the car was reportedly stolen in Springs, Gauteng, this month,” he said. He said although no one has been arrested yet, police will continue to look for the suspects. You must be SIGNED IN to read comments He urged anyone with information that may assist in apprehending the perpetrators to call CrimeStop on 08600 10111 or send information via MYSAPSAPP. Provincial police commissioner Lieutenant-General Semakaleng Manamela has commended the SANDF for doing a great job. “The cry by South Africans with regards to theft, hijacking and robbery of cars destined to neighbouring countries has been heard and the state agencies are working collaboratively to address this challenge, hence this success,” she said. 